Let $\left\{\varphi_{n}ight\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ be a complete orthonormal system in a separable Hilbert space H, and $p=\sum_{i=2}^{\infty} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i}$ be a fixed point in H, where $\sum_{i=2}^{\infty}\left|\gamma_{i}ight|^{2}<+\infty$, and there are infinitely many i such that $\gamma_{i} 
eq 0$. Furthermore, let $q=\varphi_{1}+p$. Let M be the linear space formed by all finite linear combinations of the form $\sum_{i 
eq 1} \alpha_{i} \varphi_{i}$, and U be the set of all elements of the form $\alpha q+g$, where \alpha is any complex number, and $g \in M$. It is not difficult to prove that $p 
otin U$. In fact, if $p \in U$, then $p=\alpha q+g$, that is $\sum_{i=2}^{\infty} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i}=\alpha \varphi_{1}+\alpha p+g$. Since $\varphi_{1}, \varphi_{2}, \cdots$ are linearly independent, $\alpha=0$. Thus we have $g=\sum_{i=2}^{\infty} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i} \in M$. This contradicts the fact that there are infinitely many i such that $\gamma_{i} 
eq 0$. Therefore, $p 
otin U$. Since $p 
otin U$, and by the definition of U, $q \in U$, thus from the relation $p=q-\varphi_{1}$, we get $\varphi_{1} 
otin U$. Here we prove that U is dense in H. Indeed, take $x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}  eta_{i} \varphi_{i} \in H$, let $h_{n}= eta_{1} q+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left( eta_{i}- eta_{1} \gamma_{i}ight) \varphi_{i}$, then $h_{n} \in U$. Since $ eta_{1} q= eta_{1}\left(\varphi_{1}+\sum_{i=2}^{\infty} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i}ight)= eta_{1} \varphi_{1}+ eta_{1} \sum_{i=2}^{\infty} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i}$, so $ egin{aligned}x-h_{n}= & \sum_{i=1}^{\infty}  eta_{i} \varphi_{i}-\sum_{i=2}^{\infty}  eta_{1} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i}- eta_{1} \varphi_{1} \& -\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left( eta_{i}- eta_{1} \varphi_{i}ight) \varphi_{i} \= & \sum_{i=n+1}^{\infty}\left( eta_{i}- eta_{1} \gamma_{i}ight) \varphi_{i},\end{aligned}$ hence $ egin{array}{l}\left\|x-h_{n}ight\| \leqslant\left\|\sum_{i=n+1}^{\infty}  eta_{i} \varphi_{i} \mid+ight\| \sum_{i=n+1}^{\infty}  eta_{1} \gamma_{i} \varphi_{i} \| \=\left(\sum_{i=n+1}^{\infty}\left| eta_{i}ight|^{2}ight)^{ rac{1}{2}}+\left(\sum_{i=n+1}^{\infty}\left| eta_{1} \gamma_{i}ight|^{2}ight)^{ rac{1}{2}} ightarrow 0\end{array}  （n	o \infty）$, i.e., U is dense in H. Further, we prove that M is a closed subspace of U. To this end, let $g_{n} \in M, \lim _{x ightarrow \infty} g_{n}=g_{0}$, we need to prove that $g_{0} \in M$. According to the definition of M, $\left\langle\varphi_{1}, g_{n}ightangle=0(n=1,2, \cdots)$, thus $\left\langle\varphi_{1}, g_{0}ightangle=0$. Since $g_{0} \in U$, $g_{0}$ can be expressed in the form $\alpha q+g$: $g_{0}=\alpha q+g=\alpha \varphi_{1}+\alpha p+g$. Thus from $\left\langle\varphi_{1}, g_{0}ightangle=0$, we get $\alpha=0$, hence $g_{0}=g \in M$. Because in H, elements orthogonal to M are only $ eta \varphi_{1}$ (  eta is a complex number), and these elements do not belong to U, the only element orthogonal to M in U is the zero element. Thus for $q \in U$, it cannot be decomposed into $q=x_{0}+y \quad(q 
otin M)$, where $x_{0} \in M,  oldsymbol{y} \in M^{\perp}$.

