Let $X$ be any infinite-dimensional Banach space, $H$ be a Hamel basis of $X$, and assume that for any $h \in H$, $\|h\| \leqslant 1$. For any $x \in X$, $x$ can be uniquely expressed as $ egin{array}{c} x=\sum_{k} a_{k} h_{k}, h_{k} \in H. \ \|x\|_{1}=\sum_{k}\left|a_{k}ight|, \end{array}$ and let the space under this norm be Y. Then, Y must be a first category normed linear space; and when letting the identity operator on X ightarrow Y be T, then $T^{-1}$ must be a closed continuous operator from Y to X. First, we verify that $T^{-1}$ must be a continuous operator from Y to X. In fact, because for any $x \in X$, $ egin{aligned}\|T x\|_{1} & =\|x\|_{1}=\sum_{k}\left|a_{k}ight| \geqslant \sum_{k}\left\|a_{k} h_{k}ight\| \& \geqslant\left\|\sum_{k} a_{k} h_{k}ight\|=\|x\|,\end{aligned}$ it follows that $T^{-1}$ must be a continuous operator from Y to X, and hence $T^{-1}$ is also a closed operator (see [11], pp. 322-323). Next, we verify that Y is of the first category. In fact, we divide the Hamel basis H of X into any countable number of subsets $\left\{H_{n}ight\}$, such that $H_{n} \subset H_{n+1}(n=1,2, \cdots), H_{i} 
eq H_{i}(i 
eq j), H= igcup_{n=1}^{\infty} H_{n}$. Then, for any positive integer n, $span H_{n}$ has the following properties: (i) $\operatorname{span} H_{n}$ contains no interior points. In fact, taking any $x_{0} \in \operatorname{span} H_{n}$, when $x_{0}=a_{1} h_{1}+a_{2} h_{2}+\cdots+a_{k} h_{k}$, by its construction, there exists $h^{\prime} \in H_{n+1}$, making $h^{\prime} 
otin \operatorname{span} H_{n}$. Thus, taking a sequence of positive numbers $\left\{\varepsilon_{m}ight\}$ tending to zero, and setting the sequence of points $y_{m}=a_{1} h_{1}+a_{2} h_{2}+\cdots+a_{k} h_{k}+\varepsilon_{m} h^{\prime}(m=1,2,\cdots)$, it is clear that $y_{m} 
otin \operatorname{span} H_{n}(m=1,2,\cdots)$. However, $\left\|y_{m}-x_{0}ight\|_{1}=\left\|\varepsilon_{m} h^{\prime}ight\|_{1}=\varepsilon_{m} ightarrow 0(m ightarrow \infty)$. This shows that $\operatorname{span} H_{n}$ contains no interior points. (ii) $\operatorname{span} H_{n}$ is closed. In fact, if there is an element $z_{0} \in\left(\operatorname{span} H_{n}ight)^{\prime}$, and $z_{0}= eta_{1} h_{1}+ eta_{2} h_{2}+\cdots+ eta_{i} h_{i}$, then we need only prove that $\left\{h_{k}ight\}_{k=1}^{i} \subset \operatorname{span} H_{n}$. Suppose otherwise, i.e., $h_{1}, \cdots,  ar{h}_{i_{0}} 
otin \operatorname{span} H_{n}\left(i_{0} \leqslant iight)$, then when setting the sequence of points $\left\{x_{m}ight\} \subset \operatorname{span} H_{n}$ satisfying the condition $x_{m} ightarrow z_{0}(m ightarrow \infty)$, by the definition of the norm on Y, we obtain that if the point $x_{m}=\sum_{k=i_{0}+1}^{i^{(m)}} \xi_{k}^{(m)} h_{k} \left(i^{(m)} \geqslant iight)$, then $ egin{aligned}\left\|x_{m}-z_{0}ight\| & =\sum_{k=1}^{i_{0}}\left| eta_{k}ight|+\sum_{k=i_{0}+1}^{i^{(m)}}\left|\xi_{k}^{(m)}- eta_{k}ight| \& \geqslant \sum_{k=1}^{i_{0}}\left| eta_{k}ight| 
eq 0\end{aligned}$ (here, we stipulate that when $k>i$ $ eta_{k}=0$). This contradicts equation (1). Thus, $\operatorname{span} H_{n}$ is closed. Combining (i) and (ii), we know that each $\operatorname{span} H_{n}$ is nowhere dense in Y, hence $Y= igcup_{n=1}^{\infty} \operatorname{span} H_{n}$ is of the first category. Note that the above counterexample shows that the domain D(T) of the operator T being a second category normed linear space is not an essential condition of the closed graph theorem. In other words, we can indeed find a closed linear operator defined on a first category normed linear space and taking values in another Banach space, such that it is also continuous.

