rationale:
For example, let X be an infinite-dimensional linear space,  $\mathscr{B}$  be the family of all convex balanced absorbing sets in X. Hence, there is a unique locally convex topology $	au$ on X, such that $\mathscr{B}$ is a local base of neighborhoods of the o point in $(X, 	au)$. Thus, $(X, 	au)$ is a barrel space. It is easy to verify that $	au$ is the strongest locally convex topology on X, so $X^{\#}=X^{\prime}$, i.e., every linear functional on X is continuous. It is proved that every proper subspace S of the linear space X must be the intersection of all maximal subspaces containing S. In fact, since $X  ackslash S 
eq \varnothing$, there exists $x_{0} \in X, x_{0} 
otin S$. Let $\left\{h_{\alpha }ight\}$ be a Hamel basis of S, and expand $\left\{h_{\alpha}ight\}$ into a Hamel basis $H=\left\{h^{\prime}{ }_{\alpha}ight\}$ of X containing the point $x_{0}$. Then define a linear functional f on X such that $f\left(x_{0}ight)=1$, and $f=0$ on S. Thus, $f^{\perp}=\{x \mid f(x)=0\} \supset S$, and $x_{0} 
otin f^{\perp}$. Therefore, $S= igcap_{f \in X^{\prime}} f^{\perp}$. Furthermore, every subspace of $(X, 	au)$ is closed. In fact, without loss of generality, assume S is a proper subspace of X. Since for $f \in X^{\#}$, we have $f \in X^{\prime}$, $f^{\perp}=\{x \mid f(x)=0\}$ is the closed maximal subspace of $(X, 	au)$. As proved earlier, S is the intersection of all maximal subspaces containing S, so S is also closed. Let $X= igcup_{n=1}^{\infty} S_{n}$, where $S_{n}$ is a proper subspace of X, then $S_{n}$ is a closed proper subspace of X, hence $S_{n}$ is nowhere dense, i.e., X is a barrel space of the first category.

